---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The mission, methodology, and values of the Historical Translation Project™."
>
  <Hero
    label="About the Institute"
    headline="We Translate.\nWe Research.\nWe Formulate."
    subheadline="The Historical Translation Project™ is an independent research institute dedicated to the rigorous scholarly translation of pre-modern botanical and medical traditions, and to their thoughtful synthesis with contemporary nutritional science."
  />

  <Section label="Mission" title="Our Founding Commitment">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-start">
      <div class="prose-htp">
        <p>
          The Historical Translation Project™ was founded on a conviction that the vast pharmacopoeial literature of classical Islamic, Jewish, and Greco-Roman medicine represents a largely untapped resource for contemporary wellness. Not because the past was always right — it was not — but because the accumulated clinical observations of centuries of practice contain signals that modern research is only beginning to validate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our work is deliberately disciplined. We do not romanticize historical medicine. We do not claim that classical physicians possessed secret knowledge suppressed by modern institutions. We do not make medical promises. What we do claim is that a rigorous reading of this literature, combined with a careful evaluation of contemporary phytochemical evidence, can yield formulation insights of genuine quality.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every product in our system is the result of this process: historical excavation, mechanistic evaluation, and formulation integrity — held to DSHEA compliance standards and expressed in the precise language of nutritional support, not therapeutic promise.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-6">
        {[
          ['Scholarly Rigor', 'We work from primary sources in Arabic, Hebrew, and Latin. We cite. We attribute. We acknowledge uncertainty.'],
          ['Mechanistic Integrity', 'Every historical botanical we use is evaluated for identified phytochemical mechanisms, not just historical use.'],
          ['Compliance First', 'We operate within DSHEA boundaries not as a constraint, but as an expression of our commitment to honest communication.'],
          ['Institutional Voice', 'We write and speak as researchers, not as marketers. Our tone reflects the gravity of the tradition we are translating.'],
        ].map(([title, body]) => (
          <div class="border-l-2 border-gold/40 pl-6">
            <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-navy mb-2">{title}</h3>
            <p class="font-sans text-sm text-navy/65 leading-relaxed">{body}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section label="Methodology" title="How We Work" dark>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl text-cream mb-6">The Translation Discipline</h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Our core methodology begins in the archives. Our research editors work with primary texts in their original languages — Arabic, Judeo-Arabic, Aramaic, Hebrew, and medieval Latin — rather than relying on secondary translations, which introduce layers of interpretive drift.
        </p>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
          We identify specific compound preparations, dosing frameworks, and therapeutic rationales, then map them onto modern botanical nomenclature. Where possible, we trace the transmission of a formula across traditions — how a Dioscoridean preparation was adapted by al-Razi, refined by Ibn Sina, transmitted to Maimonides, and encountered again in the Catalan school of the thirteenth century.
        </p>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          This transmission history is not merely antiquarian. When a compound appears in multiple independent traditions over a span of centuries, the convergence carries evidential weight beyond any single tradition's authority.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl text-cream mb-6">The Synthesis Standard</h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Historical identification is necessary but not sufficient. Each botanically identified compound must then pass through a contemporary evidence filter: Are there identified active constituents? Is there in vitro or in vivo mechanistic data? Are there human clinical trials, or at minimum, compelling observational data?
        </p>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
          We apply a tiered evidence standard and are transparent about where the evidence is strong, where it is preliminary, and where historical tradition is running ahead of modern validation. We do not hide gaps in the evidence base — we describe them.
        </p>
        <p class="font-sans text-cream/65 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The result is a formulation approach that neither dismisses historical knowledge as pre-scientific folklore, nor uncritically elevates it as ancestral wisdom beyond scrutiny. Both extremes misread the record.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section label="Values">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      {[
        ['Epistemic Honesty', 'We distinguish between what is known, what is suggested, and what is speculated. These are not the same, and we never treat them as though they are.'],
        ['Institutional Gravity', 'The civilizations whose medicine we translate approached health with seriousness, patience, and intellectual humility. We aspire to that same disposition.'],
        ['Clinical Humility', 'We are scholars and formulators, not physicians. We do not diagnose. We do not prescribe. We do not advise on specific medical conditions. We provide support for healthy physiological function — and we stop there.'],
        ['Transparency', 'We publish our ingredient specifications, standardizations, and sourcing rationales. There are no proprietary blends, no hidden doses.'],
        ['Accessibility', 'The scholarship of classical medicine should not be locked behind institutional paywalls or professional gatekeeping. Our publications are written for intelligent general readers, not only specialists.'],
        ['Long Horizon', 'We are building a body of work meant to endure — translations, formulations, and research that will be worth reading in fifty years. This shapes every editorial and formulation decision we make.'],
      ].map(([title, body]) => (
        <div class="card-base">
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-navy mb-3">{title}</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-sm text-navy/65 leading-relaxed">{body}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </Section>

  <section class="bg-gold/10 border-y border-gold/20 py-20">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <div class="ornament mb-6">✦</div>
      <blockquote class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-navy italic leading-relaxed mb-6">
        "The physician who knows only the medicine of his own era knows very little medicine."
      </blockquote>
      <p class="text-xs font-sans text-navy/40 tracking-widest uppercase">— Attributed to Ibn Sina (Avicenna), c. 1025</p>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Get in Touch</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
